						<h4>Ashley Wooley</h4>
						<h5>Maid of Honor &amp; Sister</h5>
						<p>
							...well technically "sister-in-law", but she really is so much more to me than just "my brother’s wife", that I decided to drop the "in-law" indefinitely. I met Ashley at my brother’s apartment when they both attended the University of Idaho, and we’ve been causing a ruckus ever since. She’s been my voice of reason when I feel like I’m about to have a bridezilla meltdown, and will entertain me as I compare 10 shades of white during hour 8 of wedding dress shopping. She’s the smartest decision my brother has ever made, and I’m eternally grateful I get the reap the benefits.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="bridesmaid">
					<figure>
						<img src="/images/courtneym.jpg" alt="Courtney M.">
					</figure>
					<div>
						<h4>Courtney McKeehan</h4>
						<h5>Bridesmaid</h5>
						<p>
							In the course of our lives, Courtney and I have been friends longer than we haven’t. When I think about the things in my youth that I probably shouldn’t haven got away with, Courtney was by my side, making sure that whatever plan we thought up, went smoothly. Her need for adventure has only grown with time, and whether she’s playing with Tigers in Thailand, or celebrating St. Patty’s day in Ireland, the distance has never hindered our near 2 decade bond. 
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="bridesmaid">
					<figure>
						<img src="/images/tierney.jpg" alt="Tierney">
					</figure>
					<div>
						<h4>Tierney Cooke</h4>
						<h5>Bridesmaid</h5>
						<p>
							Thank goodness for unlimited data plans, I don’t think I could have survived without one. Despite living on opposite sides of the state in college, &amp; now opposite ends of the country for the entirety of our post collegiate lives, very few hours go by when we aren’t in touch. From the Southwest to the Northeast, a three hour time difference is nothing against our friendship. She’s my go-to for every "Guess what" and "You won’t believe this". 
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="bridesmaid">
					<figure>
						<img src="/images/melissa.jpg" alt="Melissa">
					</figure>
					<div>
						<h4>Melissa Barham</h4>
						<h5>Bridesmaid</h5>
						<p>
							You know those horror stories about being paired up with the worst dorm-mate your freshmen year? I could’t tell you if they’re true or not, because I had the honest pleasure of sharing the most spacious 200 sqft dorm room with Melissa. Despite the fact it was haunted, and our window was inconveniently located right above the WSU marching band’s outdoor practicing alley... all of my favorite Pullman memories happened with Melissa in tow. From teaching me the "Soulja Boy" dance so I wasn’t left out at frat parties, to grabbing a slice of our favorite cake from the dining hall to save for me for later, I couldn’t imagine saying "I do" to my next life adventure without Melissa by my side.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="bridesmaid">
					<figure>
						<img src="/images/courtneyh.jpg" alt="Courtney H.">
					</figure>
					<div>
						<h4>Courtney Hathaway</h4>
						<h5>Bridesmaid</h5>
						<p>
							You don’t know what you’ve got till its gone, and its safe to say that Courtney and I took our sanity for granted before starting the Interior Design Program at Washington State.  It might have been the fumes from our rendering markers, or maybe having to scrape layers of ice off our windshields when we left our studio at 3am in the middle of December and it was -12 degrees, but struggling at life so immensely is completely doable when you have Courtney as a friend to tell you jokes and make you laugh when you feel like crying. I can always count on her to find the silver lining to any situation and I am so lucky to have her as the brightest ray of sunshine in my life.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
